  \(\displaystyle \sin x=\frac{-3\pm\sqrt{9-4(4)(-5)}}{8}
  =\frac{-3\pm\sqrt{9+80}}{8}
  =\frac{-3\pm\sqrt{89}}{8}\) <marks>M1</marks>
- Conclude valid root: Since \(\frac{-3-\sqrt{89}}{8} < -1\), it is rejected. Only \(\frac{-3+\sqrt{89}}{8}\) is admissible. <marks>A1</marks>

steps.content:
The phase shift is the horizontal displacement. We find this by determining where the argument of the sine function is equal to zero (where the cycle 'starts'):

$$
\begin{aligned}
3x - \frac{\pi}{4} &= 0 \\
3x &= \frac{\pi}{4} \\
x &= \frac{\pi}{12}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $x$ is positive, the **phase shift is $\frac{\pi}{12}$ units to the right**.

